<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
This squamulose, isidiate species contains atranorin and parvifoliellin (Fig. 8C); characters it shares with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. concinna" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="concinna">P. concinna</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. rappiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="rappiana">P. rappiana</taxonomicName>
. The molecular phylogeny (Fig. 1) shows that the three species are not closely related, though; rather 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. parvifoliella" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="parvifoliella">P. parvifoliella</taxonomicName>
belongs in a clade together with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. africana" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="africana">P. africana</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. ochroxantha" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="ochroxantha">P. ochroxantha</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. swinscowii" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="swinscowii">P. swinscowii</taxonomicName>
. We have sequenced material from Indonesia and Thailand, and here report the species as new to Asia and Melanesia, i.e. from Indonesia, Papua New Guinea, The Philippines, and Thailand.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
